The course will examine key thinkers who have contributed to philosophical reflections on time such as Augustine, Heidegger, Benjamin and Koselleck. We will ask how conceptions of time are related to temporal distinctions of modern and postmodern. Although the course is open to all students who have already taken some introductory course of philosophy, it is intended for upper-level students.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The course aims to familiarise students with the philosophy of time and history within continental philosophy.

Students will also develop the following skills:

Self-Management Skills - time management, goal setting and self-motivation.

Academic skills - reading academic texts, academic writing and critical thinking.

People skills - how to communicate and participate in team work.

These will be developed during the seminar with group work and include skills for debating and for writing a well structured paper in philosophy.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  The learning outcomes are a firm understanding of philosophy of time and history within continental philosophy. Having passed the course, the student has also improved his or her ability to analyze philosophical texts, his or her presentations skills.
